**Core glob tokens:**

| Token | Matches | Example |
|:------|:--------|:--------|
| `*` | Any characters except `/` | `*.tf` matches `main.tf` but not `modules/main.tf` |
| `**` | Any characters including `/` (zero or more path segments) | `**/*.tf` matches `main.tf` and `modules/vpc/main.tf` |
| `?` | Exactly one character except `/` | `src/?.ts` matches `src/a.ts` but not `src/ab.ts` |
| `{a,b}` | Either `a` or `b` (brace expansion) | `**/*.{ts,tsx}` matches both `.ts` and `.tsx` files |

**Critical edge cases for architects:**

**Edge case 1 — trailing slash ambiguity.** `terraform/**` matches files *and* directories under `terraform/`. To be explicit about files only, use `terraform/**/*` (requires at least one path segment after `terraform/`).

**Edge case 2 — root anchoring.** `*.tf` matches only Terraform files in the project root. `**/*.tf` matches them anywhere. In a monorepo, always prefer `**/*.tf` unless you genuinely want root-only scope.

**Edge case 3 — dotfiles.** Many glob implementations do not match dotfiles (files starting with `.`) with `*` or `**` by default. If your conventions apply to `.eslintrc.ts` or `.prettierrc.js`, test explicitly whether your pattern covers them.

**Edge case 4 — case sensitivity.** On case-sensitive filesystems (Linux), `**/*.TSX` will not match `Button.tsx`. Standardise on lowercase extensions in patterns.

**Edge case 5 — negation patterns.** Some rule systems support `!` prefix for exclusion (e.g., `!**/node_modules/**`). Confirm whether the Claude rules engine honours negation before relying on it in production.

Schema design is where architectural judgment has the highest leverage. A poorly designed schema forces the model to hallucinate values; a well-designed schema guides the model toward honest, useful output.

### Required vs. optional (nullable) fields

Mark a field as **required** only when the source document is guaranteed to contain it. If the document might not include the information, make the field **optional** (or nullable in JSON Schema terms). A required field that is absent in the source document will be fabricated by the model to satisfy the schema — a silent, dangerous hallucination.

```json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "invoice_number": {
      "type": "string",
      "description": "Invoice identifier. Required — all invoices have one."
    },
    "purchase_order_number": {
      "type": ["string", "null"],
      "description": "PO number if referenced in the document; null if absent."
    },
    "due_date": {
      "type": ["string", "null"],
      "description": "Payment due date in ISO 8601 format (YYYY-MM-DD), or null if not stated."
    }
  },
  "required": ["invoice_number"]
}
```

By allowing `null`, you give the model a truthful exit: it can say "this information is not present" rather than inventing a plausible-looking value.

### Enum fields with `"other"` + detail string

Enum fields are powerful for controlled vocabularies, but real-world data always contains edge cases that don't fit predefined categories. The **`"other"` + detail** pattern handles this gracefully:

```json
{
  "payment_method": {
    "type": "string",
    "enum": ["credit_card", "bank_transfer", "check", "cash", "other"],
    "description": "Payment method used."
  },
  "payment_method_detail": {
    "type": ["string", "null"],
    "description": "Required when payment_method is 'other'; describes the actual method."
  }
}
```

This pattern keeps your enum closed for the common cases (enabling downstream filtering and analytics) while remaining open for the long tail. The `detail` field captures the raw value for human review.

### The `"unclear"` sentinel value

For fields where the document contains information but it is genuinely ambiguous, add `"unclear"` to the enum. This is preferable to `null` (which means "absent") and preferable to a guess (which is a hallucination).

```json
{
  "document_type": {
    "type": "string",
    "enum": ["invoice", "purchase_order", "receipt", "credit_note", "unclear"],
    "description": "Use 'unclear' if the document type cannot be determined with confidence."
  }
}
```

### Schema design decision matrix

| Situation | Recommended approach |
|:----------|:---------------------|
| Field always present in source | `required`, non-nullable |
| Field sometimes present | Optional, `type: ["string", "null"]` |
| Fixed vocabulary, exhaustive | `enum` with all values |
| Fixed vocabulary, open-ended | `enum` + `"other"` + `detail` field |
| Ambiguous but present | `enum` includes `"unclear"` |
| Computed / derivable | Omit from schema; compute in application code |
